INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f015e8ab-1b73-4b98-bb32-aff1aa6935f3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SolidJS API Layer — One HTTP Client, Interceptors, No Raw fetch in Components$escape$,
  $escape$Raw `fetch` calls scattered across SolidJS components create retry chaos and auth token drift. Instead, centralize all HTTP traffic through a single client module that owns interceptors, base URL, and error normalization.

Create an `apiClient.ts` that wraps `fetch` with a request pipeline: inject the Clerk JWT from `useAuth()` at the interceptor boundary, not inside components. Add a retry interceptor with exponential backoff for 429/503 responses. Expose typed helpers (`get<T>`, `post<T>`) that return `Promise<T>`, keeping components free of HTTP concerns.

In SolidJS, pair this with `createResource` — your data-fetching primitive. The resource fetcher function calls `apiClient.get(url)` directly; SolidJS handles Suspense integration, reactive re-fetching on signal changes, and error boundaries via `ErrorBoundary`. This keeps component code purely declarative: signal in, data out.

Never instantiate auth headers inside a `createResource` fetcher. The client layer owns cross-cutting concerns; the resource owns reactivity. Violating this boundary makes auth token rotation a component-level emergency.$escape$,
  $escape$// apiClient.ts
import { getAuth } from '@clerk/clerk-js';

async function request<T>(path: string, init: RequestInit = {}): Promise<T> {
  const { getToken } = getAuth();
  const token = await getToken();
  const res = await fetch(`${import.meta.env.VITE_API_URL}${path}`, {
    ...init,
    headers: { 'Authorization': `Bearer ${token}`, 'Content-Type': 'application/json', ...init.headers },
  });
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`${res.status}: ${await res.text()}`);
  return res.json() as Promise<T>;
}

export const apiClient = {
  get: <T>(path: string) => request<T>(path),
  post: <T>(path: string, body: unknown) => request<T>(path, { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify(body) }),
};

// In a component:
const [posts] = createResource(() => props.userId, (id) => apiClient.get<Post[]>(`/posts?userId=${id}`));$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
